      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 12b. Understanding Your Payslip -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>Understanding Your Payslip on {page.monthlyFormatted} Per Month</h2>
      <p>
        Your payslip is the official record of what you earn and what is deducted each pay period. If you are paid
        monthly on a {page.monthlyFormatted} gross salary, here is what each line on your payslip means and approximately
        what you should expect to see:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Gross pay:</strong> This is your total pay before any deductions. On a monthly payslip, this
          will show {page.monthlyFormatted}. If you receive overtime, bonuses, or commission, these will be added
          to your gross figure for that month.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Tax code:</strong> Displayed as 1257L for most employees, this tells your employer how much of your
          income is tax-free. The number 1257 means you have a Personal Allowance of £12,570. The letter L confirms
          you are entitled to the standard allowance. If your code is different, it may affect your take-home pay.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>PAYE tax:</strong> This is the income tax deducted under the Pay As You Earn system. Your employer
          calculates this based on your tax code and earnings.{paysTax
            ? ` Expect to see approximately ${formatCurrency(page.england.incomeTax / 12)} deducted each month.`
            : ' At your salary level, this should show £0 as you are within the Personal Allowance.'}
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>National Insurance:</strong> Shown as "NI" or "Employee NI" on your payslip.{paysNI
            ? ` You should see approximately ${formatCurrency(page.england.nationalInsurance / 12)} deducted monthly.`
            : ' At your salary level, this should show £0 as your earnings are below the Primary Threshold.'}
          Your NI category letter (usually A for most employees) determines which rates apply.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Net pay:</strong> This is the amount actually paid into your bank account after all deductions.
          On {page.monthlyFormatted} gross, your net monthly pay should be approximately <strong>{page.englandFormatted.netMonthly}</strong>.
          This is sometimes labelled "take-home pay" or "total payment".
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If any of these figures do not match what you expect based on this breakdown, check your tax code first. Common
        reasons for discrepancies include an incorrect tax code, student loan deductions, workplace pension contributions,
        or benefits in kind. You can view and update your tax code through your HMRC Personal Tax Account online.
      </p>

      {page.tier === 'below-pa' && (
        <>
          <h2>Why You Might Still Need to File a Tax Return</h2>
          <p>
            Even though you earn below the Personal Allowance and pay no income tax, there are situations where HMRC
            may require you to complete a Self Assessment tax return. These include:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Self-employment income:</strong> If you have any freelance or self-employment income alongside
              your employed earnings, you must file a return if your total self-employment income exceeds £1,000
              (the trading allowance).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Rental income:</strong> If you receive income from renting out property, you may need to declare
              it even if your total income is below the Personal Allowance.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Savings and investment income:</strong> While the Personal Savings Allowance and dividend allowance
              cover most situations, unusually high returns may trigger a filing requirement.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Reclaiming overpaid tax:</strong> If tax has been deducted incorrectly (for instance, you
              started a new job mid-year with an emergency tax code), filing a return or contacting HMRC can help
              you get a refund.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </>
      )}

      {page.tier === 'basic-rate' && (
        <>
          <h2>How a Pay Rise Would Affect Your Take-Home</h2>
          <p>
            If you are earning {page.monthlyFormatted} per month and considering negotiating a pay rise, it helps to
            understand how additional income is taxed. At your current salary level, your <strong>marginal tax
            rate</strong> is {page.englandFormatted.marginalTaxRate}. This means for every extra £1 you earn, you
            keep {formatCurrency(1 - (page.england.marginalTaxRate / 100), true)} after tax and NI.
          </p>
          <p>
            For example, a £100 per month pay rise ({formatCurrency(1200)} per year) would increase your annual gross
            from {page.annualFormatted} to {formatCurrency(page.annual + 1200)}. After the basic rate income tax (20%)
            and NI ({(NI_MAIN_RATE * 100).toFixed(0)}%), you would keep approximately {formatCurrency(1200 * (1 - page.england.marginalTaxRate / 100))} of
            that £1,200, adding roughly {formatCurrency(1200 * (1 - page.england.marginalTaxRate / 100) / 12)} to your
            monthly take-home pay.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is why understanding marginal rates matters when evaluating job offers or negotiating salary increases.
            The headline increase is always more than what you actually receive in your bank account.
          </p>
        </>
      )}

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 12d. Building Financial Security -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>Building Financial Security on {page.monthlyFormatted} Per Month</h2>

      <p>
        Whatever your salary level, building financial security is about making consistent, informed decisions over
        time. On a take home of {page.englandFormatted.netMonthly} per month, the strategies that work best depend
        on your current situation, your goals, and how much flexibility your budget allows. Here is how to think
        about money management at {page.annualFormatted} per year.
      </p>

      {lifeBracket === 'minimal' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            Financial planning on {page.monthlyFormatted} per month starts with understanding exactly where your money
            goes. With {page.englandFormatted.netMonthly} coming in, every pound counts. Track your income and spending
            for a full month, writing down every purchase however small. Many people are surprised to find that daily
            expenses like a coffee or a bus ticket add up to a significant portion of their monthly income. This
            awareness alone can change how you spend.
          </p>
          <p>
            Even at {page.monthlyFormatted} per month, building a savings habit is worthwhile. Starting with £5 or £10
            per month might feel insignificant, but the habit itself is what matters. Once you are accustomed to putting
            money aside before spending, increasing the amount as your income grows becomes natural. Many banks now offer
            round up savings features on debit cards, which automatically save the spare change from each transaction.
            Over the course of a year, these small amounts can accumulate into a useful emergency buffer.
          </p>
          <p>
            Looking ahead from {page.monthlyFormatted} per month, consider what steps would increase your earning
            potential. Even modest investments in skills or qualifications, many of which are available free through
            local colleges and online platforms, can lead to better paid opportunities within months. The UK government
            funds free courses for adults through the National Skills Fund, covering areas from digital literacy to
            business management. These cost you nothing but time and can meaningfully shift your income trajectory.
          </p>
        </>
      ) : lifeBracket === 'parttime' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            Managing finances on {page.monthlyFormatted} per month requires a structured approach that separates
            essential spending from everything else. Start by listing your fixed monthly obligations: housing, council
            tax share, energy bills, phone, and transport. Subtract these from your take home of
            {page.englandFormatted.netMonthly}, and the remaining amount is what you have for food, personal items,
            and discretionary spending. Knowing this number precisely removes the anxiety of guessing and helps you
            avoid the end of month crunch.
          </p>
          <p>
            Debt management deserves special attention at this salary level. If you carry any balances on credit cards,
            overdrafts, or personal loans, the interest reduces your effective income further. Prioritising repayment
            starting with the highest interest rate balances frees up money over time. If multiple debts feel
            overwhelming, free advice services such as StepChange, National Debtline, and Citizens Advice can help
            you create a manageable repayment plan and may negotiate with creditors on your behalf.
          </p>
          <p>
            Building an emergency fund on {page.monthlyFormatted} per month is challenging but not impossible. Aim for
            an initial target of £200 to £500, enough to cover a minor emergency such as an urgent dental bill, a
            broken appliance, or an unexpected travel cost. Setting up a standing order for £20 per month on payday
            means this target is reachable within one to two years. The security of knowing you have a small financial
            cushion reduces stress noticeably and gives you more confidence when making decisions about your work.
          </p>
          <p>
            State pension contributions matter even at this income. If you earn above the Lower Earnings Limit of £6,708
            per year, your employer reports your earnings to HMRC and the year counts towards your State Pension
            qualifying years. You need 35 qualifying years for the full amount. Checking your National Insurance record
            online through the government website shows how many qualifying years you have and whether any action is
            needed to protect your future pension.
          </p>
        </>
      ) : lifeBracket === 'nearpa' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            At {page.monthlyFormatted} per month, your financial planning can move beyond basic survival budgeting into
            building genuine security. With {page.englandFormatted.netMonthly} per month, you have enough income to
            create a proper budget with categories for housing, food, transport, bills, savings, and personal spending.
            The 50/30/20 framework, which allocates 50% to needs, 30% to wants, and 20% to savings, is a useful
            starting point, although you may need to adjust the ratios to reflect housing costs in your particular area.
          </p>
          <p>
            Your workplace pension is one of the most valuable financial tools available to you. Under auto enrolment
            rules, your employer must contribute at least 3% of your qualifying earnings, while you contribute 5%. This
            means that for every £100 of qualifying earnings, your pension pot grows by £8 before investment returns are
            even considered. If your employer offers to match additional contributions beyond the legal minimum, that is
            effectively free money and one of the best financial decisions you can make at any income level.
          </p>
          <p>
            An ISA is the natural next step once you have a basic emergency fund in place. Cash ISAs offer a safe home
            for savings with interest that is completely free from tax. For longer term goals, a Lifetime ISA adds a
            25% government bonus to your contributions (up to £1,000 per year on a maximum of £4,000). If you are under
            40 and saving for your first home, the Lifetime ISA is particularly attractive because the government tops
            up every pound you save by 25p. That is a guaranteed 25% return before any interest is earned.
          </p>
          <p>
            Contents insurance is worth considering even at {page.monthlyFormatted} per month. It costs as little as
            £5 to £10 per month and protects your belongings against theft, fire, and water damage. Replacing a laptop,
            a phone, and basic furniture after a burglary or flood could easily cost £1,000 to £2,000, which would be
            devastating on this salary without insurance. The small monthly premium buys significant peace of mind.
          </p>
        </>
      ) : lifeBracket === 'lower' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            Financial planning on {page.monthlyFormatted} per month shifts from managing scarcity to making strategic
            choices. Your take home of {page.englandFormatted.netMonthly} provides enough headroom to pursue multiple
            financial goals at once. The most effective approach is to automate your finances so that savings, pension
            contributions, and bill payments leave your account on payday. Whatever remains after these automatic
            transfers is genuinely available to spend, and you can use it freely knowing that your essentials and future
            are already covered.
          </p>
          <p>
            Building an emergency fund of three to six months of essential expenses should be a top priority. At your
            spending level, this means accumulating between {emergencyFund3mo} and {emergencyFund6mo} in an easily
            accessible savings account. This fund serves as your personal safety net against job loss, illness, or
            unexpected major expenses. Without it, a single financial shock can push you into debt that takes years to
            clear. With it, you can handle most emergencies from a position of strength rather than panic.
          </p>
          <p>
            If you are considering buying a home, understanding the numbers at {page.monthlyFormatted} per month is
            essential. Mortgage lenders typically offer 4 to 4.5 times your annual gross salary, which means you could
            potentially borrow up to {mortgageMax}. Combined with a deposit, this determines the property value you can
            target. Government schemes such as the First Homes programme and shared ownership can bridge the gap if
            property prices in your area exceed what your salary alone supports. Starting your deposit savings early
            demonstrates the financial discipline that lenders assess favourably.
          </p>
          <p>
            Tax efficient saving and investing deserve attention at this income level. Your annual ISA allowance of
            £20,000 lets you shelter a meaningful amount of savings from tax. For basic rate taxpayers, a stocks and
            shares ISA offers the potential for higher returns than cash over the long term, with all gains and
            dividends remaining tax free. For pension savings, contributing above the auto enrolment minimum through
            salary sacrifice builds your retirement fund faster and simultaneously reduces your income tax and National
            Insurance deductions.
          </p>
        </>
      ) : (
        <>
          <p>
            At {page.monthlyFormatted} per month, your financial planning can incorporate strategies that are simply not
            available at lower income levels. Your take home of {page.englandFormatted.netMonthly} supports a comfortable
            lifestyle while also allowing for serious wealth building. The key distinction at this level is moving from
            merely saving money to actively investing it, because cash sitting in a current account loses purchasing
            power to inflation over time. Making your surplus income work for you is the single most important
            financial shift at this salary level.
          </p>
          <p>
            Your pension strategy deserves careful thought. Every £80 you contribute to a pension becomes £100 in your
            pot thanks to basic rate tax relief, and if your employer matches additional contributions, the returns
            multiply further. Consider increasing your pension contribution by 1% each time you receive a pay rise. This
            gradual approach builds a substantial retirement fund over your career without any noticeable impact on your
            lifestyle, because you never become accustomed to spending the additional income in the first place.
          </p>
          <p>
            Investment diversification becomes genuinely relevant at this salary level. Beyond your workplace pension and
            a cash emergency fund, consider allocating {savingsAt10pct} per month to a stocks and shares ISA invested in
            diversified index funds. The long term average return of global stock markets has historically exceeded 7%
            per year before inflation, compared to cash savings that typically lag behind the rising cost of living. A
            consistent monthly investment maintained over 20 years can grow into a significant sum through compound
            returns.
          </p>
          <p>
            Estate planning and protection insurance become worthwhile as your income and assets grow. A basic will
            costs between £150 and £300 through a solicitor and ensures your assets are distributed according to your
            wishes. Life insurance, if you have dependents, provides financial security for your family. Critical
            illness cover pays a lump sum if you are diagnosed with a specified serious condition. At
            {page.monthlyFormatted} per month, the premiums for these policies are affordable relative to the
            protection they provide, and they form a responsible part of any comprehensive financial plan.
          </p>
        </>
      )}

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 12e. Regional Cost of Living -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>How {page.monthlyFormatted} Per Month Compares Across UK Regions</h2>

      <p>
        The purchasing power of {page.monthlyFormatted} per month varies enormously depending on where you live in
        the United Kingdom. Housing costs drive the biggest regional differences, but food, transport, childcare,
        and entertainment also vary. The ONS publishes regional price parities showing that London prices sit
        roughly 10% to 15% above the national average, while the North East is around 5% below. Here is what
        that means in practice for your take home of {page.englandFormatted.netMonthly}.
      </p>

      {regionBracket === 'low' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            For someone earning {page.monthlyFormatted} per month, choosing where to live can effectively change the
            value of your salary. The same take home pay of {page.englandFormatted.netMonthly} stretches much further
            in Burnley or Blackpool than in Bath or Brighton. The most affordable regions include the North East of
            England, where a studio flat in cities like Middlesbrough or Sunderland costs as little as £300 per month,
            and Northern Ireland, where Belfast offers significantly cheaper rents than any major English city. Wales
            provides excellent value too, particularly in the Valleys and smaller coastal towns.
          </p>
          <p>
            The South East and Greater London present a starkly different picture. In these areas, housing costs alone
            can exceed your entire monthly salary of {page.monthlyFormatted}. If you live in a high cost area and earn
            this amount, remote or hybrid work arrangements can allow you to earn a city wage while paying rural
            housing costs. Even jobs that were traditionally location specific, such as customer service and data
            processing, now frequently offer working from home options that can transform your financial situation
            without changing your actual pay.
          </p>
        </>
      ) : regionBracket === 'mid' ? (
        <>
          <p>
            Your salary of {page.monthlyFormatted} per month goes furthest in the regions where housing costs are
            lowest. In the North East, Yorkshire, the East Midlands, and the North West, average rents for a one
            bedroom flat range from £400 to £550, leaving you with a meaningful portion of your
            {page.englandFormatted.netMonthly} take home for other expenses. Scotland offers particularly good value
            in cities like Aberdeen, Inverness, and Perth, where rents are lower than Edinburgh and Glasgow but local
            amenities and job markets remain strong. Wales and Northern Ireland also provide excellent value at
            this salary level.
          </p>
          <p>
            London sits at the other extreme. Average rents for a one bedroom flat in the capital exceed £1,500, which
            is more than your entire gross monthly salary. Even outer London boroughs like Havering, Bromley, and
            Bexley see studio rents starting around £800. If your job requires proximity to London, exploring satellite
            towns with fast commuter rail links, such as Luton, Stevenage, or Reading, can dramatically reduce your
            housing costs while keeping the capital within reach for work. The difference between what
            {rentBudget30} buys in Sheffield versus central London is remarkable.
          </p>
        </>
      ) : (
        <>
          <p>
            At {page.monthlyFormatted} per month, your choice of UK region has a direct and measurable impact on your
            quality of life. Cities in the Midlands and the North offer the best combination of affordable living and
            strong job markets. Birmingham, Manchester, Leeds, Sheffield, and Nottingham all have thriving economies
            with opportunities across multiple sectors, while housing costs remain significantly below southern levels.
            A two bedroom flat in Sheffield costs roughly half what a similar property in Reading would command. Your
            housing budget of {rentBudget30} per month rents a spacious property in most northern cities, while the
            same amount barely covers a studio in parts of the South East.
          </p>
          <p>
            Scotland offers a compelling proposition for workers at {page.monthlyFormatted} per month. The Scottish
            income tax system applies different rates, but as the comparison table above shows, the difference in take
            home is often modest. Scotland compensates with several advantages including free prescriptions, more
            generous student finance support, and generally lower housing costs outside Edinburgh. Glasgow, Aberdeen,
            and Dundee all maintain strong job markets with notably lower living costs than their English equivalents.
            If remote work allows you to choose your location freely, the financial case for Scotland is strong at
            this salary level.
          </p>
        </>
      )}

      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- 12f. Understanding Your True Hourly Rate -->
      <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <h2>Your True Hourly Rate on {page.monthlyFormatted} Per Month</h2>

      <p>
        Many people focus on their monthly or annual salary without considering what they actually earn per hour
        after tax. On a gross salary of {page.monthlyFormatted} per month, your headline hourly rate is
        {page.hourlyGross} based on a standard 37.5 hour working week. Once income tax and National Insurance are
        deducted, your real hourly earning drops to approximately {hourlyNet}. This is your true hourly rate: the
        amount you genuinely receive for each hour of your working time.
      </p>

      <p>
        Understanding this number helps you make better decisions about both work and spending. If you earn
        {hourlyNet} per hour after tax, then a £50 purchase represents roughly {hoursFor50} hours of your working
        life. A £500 purchase represents {hoursFor500} hours. Thinking about spending in terms of hours worked
        rather than pounds spent adds useful context to buying decisions. This does not mean you should never treat
        yourself, but it gives you a concrete way to evaluate whether a purchase is genuinely worth the time you
        traded to earn the money.
      </p>

      <p>
        Your effective hourly rate also matters when evaluating overtime or additional work opportunities. If
        overtime is paid at time and a half, your gross hourly rate of {page.hourlyGross} would increase to
        approximately {formatCurrency(page.annual / (52 * 37.5) * 1.5)} per hour for those extra hours. However,
        the additional income is taxed at your marginal rate, so the true benefit is less than the headline figure.
        {page.tier === 'basic-rate'
          ? ` At your current salary level, each extra pound earned is subject to 20% income tax and ${(NI_MAIN_RATE * 100).toFixed(0)}% National Insurance, meaning you keep about 72p of every additional pound.`
          : ` Since your salary is within the Personal Allowance, any extra earnings remain largely untaxed until you cross the ${formatCurrency(PERSONAL_ALLOWANCE)} annual threshold.`}
        Knowing this helps you decide whether extra hours are worth the time, or whether that time would be better
        invested in rest, family, or professional development that could lead to a higher base salary in the future.
      </p>

